##New Crown Disease will promote the pharmaceutical industry which development and change?

In the short term, clinical advances in disease-related OTC medicines, consumables for household and medical equipment and potential Miracle Drugs will accelerate; in the long term, the pharmaceutical industry may be catalysed by the epidemic to usher in new changes, financial Investment in public health is likely to increase

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
-- Li Zhan, Liu Yazhou

Editor / Hao Zhou

Whether it is the pathogen itself, the clinical manifestations of the disease, the characteristics of the epidemic, or even the response of the government, enterprises and the public, the current outbreak of pneumonia in COVID-19 bears some resemblance to the SARS epidemic in 2003.

SARS and the 2019-nCoV, both of which belong to the genus coronaviruses, are airborne and human-to-human, causing very severe respiratory disease in the clinic and later developing into severe epidemics that were fought by the whole country, and eventually caused a certain negative impact on the macro-economy. SARS cases first appeared in Guangdong in November 2002, but the early epidemic situation was not taken seriously until March 2003, when the epidemic spread to Beijing, WHO issued a global alert, the SARS epidemic really entered the public field of vision. With the outbreak, the government began a number of emergency measures in mid-to-late April 2003, and eventually the epidemic began to fade in mid-to late May.

Available evidence suggests that cases of COVID-19 pneumonia began to appear in Wuhan at the end of 2019 and that the outbreak began and came into public view around January 20,2020. Since late January, governments at all levels began to take a number of emergency measures, new pneumonia epidemic inflection point is gradually emerging.

1. Review of SARS epidemic situation from 2003 to 2019-nCoV

1.1. Influence of SARS on the development of pharmaceutical and biological industry

During the period of SARS outbreak from April to May 2003, the growth rate of the main business income of China's pharmaceutical manufacturing industry increased to a certain extent, and the cumulative growth rate reached 22% in May 2003, the highest in 2002-2004. But after the outbreak ended, the industry's growth rate gradually returned and stabilized.

Chart 2china's pharmaceutical manufacturing industry grew slightly during SARS

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Source: Wind

In the outbreak of SARS in 2003, the domestic pharmaceutical industry to traditional Chinese medicine, biological products, chemical raw materials and chemicals-based. Take the capital market as an example. At that time, the market value of these four sub-industries accounted for 32% , 21% , 15% and 7% respectively of the total market value of the pharmaceutical industry Representative leading companies such as Harbin Pharmaceutical Stock, north China Pharmaceutical, Baiyun Mountain, China Resources Sanjiu and Tong Ren Tang are also Chinese medicine or chemical raw material pharmaceutical enterprises.

In addition, at that time, not long after China joined the WTO, many foreign-funded pharmaceutical enterprises had not really made great strides in developing in China, so the domestic pharmaceutical industry was still quite dependent on traditional Chinese medicine in clinical practice, and chemical medicine was characterized by more than fine, effective, high-quality chemicals are scarce, and the so-called "Western medicine" is still relatively low-end drug-based raw materials, medical devices and other industrial products are still in the early stage of exploration.

As a result, the pharmaceutical manufacturing sector, which is dominated by proprietary Chinese medicines and chemical agents for clinical end-use, was positively stimulated during this period, showing a performance similar to that of the industry as a whole, that is, short-term growth was stimulated to a certain extent, but after the outbreak, it basically returned to the annual growth rate, with Chinese medicine having the most obvious boosting effect, while raw material medicines and other industrial chains, which are relatively remote from clinical use, have relatively small fluctuations. For industries such as sanitary materials and medical devices, the impact is relatively lagging, but is more likely to be an industry's medium-to long-term growth stimulus.

In short, the overall impact of the SARS epidemic on the pharmaceutical industry is positive, subject to the medical and technical conditions of the time, the beneficiary sub-industries are mainly Chinese medicine and other clinical drug, the positive impact is mainly reflected in the short-term quarter. In the long run, after the SARS epidemic ended, the government's investment in the health care sector increased significantly. Both National Health Insurance and the construction of the public health system achieved rapid development in the following years, even the epidemic may have prompted the new reforms. Therefore, the epidemic may be the entire industry in the medium and long-term positive development of the catalyst.

1.2. Market Performance of pharmaceutical and biological industry during SARS

Market, the industry as a whole in the short-term clearly outperform the market. However, from the perspective of the whole year of 2003, SARS had little influence on the whole market and the pharmaceutical industry, and the pharmaceutical industry did not show the characteristics of "benefiting industry" .

It should be noted that, although the SARS epidemic lasted longer, the period of time during which the outbreak of SARS really concentrated and led to the national fight against the epidemic and caused the temporary economic shutdown was mainly concentrated in the second quarter of 2003, especially from mid to late April to mid to early May. As a result, the time horizon for both the economic shutdown and the trading of capital markets is narrower.

Symbolic events that can help us to divide the time interval between the outbreak of SARS are: the Central Committee began to take a number of emergency measures on April 17,2003; on April 20,2003, the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China abolished the inner-party posts of Meng Xuenong, mayor of Beijing, and Zhang Wenkang, Minister of Health; on April 21,2003, the State Council established the anti-SARS headquarters; on April 24,2003, primary and secondary schools in Beijing began to suspend classes, after about three weeks of tight control, after the May Day holiday, the epidemic began to turn the corner, and finally on May 22,2003, high school students began to return to school.

On the other hand, during the SARS epidemic, the a share market also delayed the opening of a week. Considering the SARS outbreak area we have divided, we believe that the capital market began to pay attention to the SARS outbreak around April 20,2003, and made a drastic response, by 16 May 2003, one week after the resumption of trading, expectations were more or less fully reflected. Specifically, the Shanghai composite index fell 3.0% from 1,603 points on April 18 to 1,554 points on May 16, with the biggest drop of 7.3% , while the SHENWAN pharmaceutical index fell 2.7% from 1,288 points to 1,252, with the biggest drop of 4.9% .

Within the industry, when SARS broke out in 2003, there were only 96 listed companies in the a-share pharmaceutical industry with a total market value of about 260 billion yuan.

In the medium-term dimension of one year, the four sub-industries are basically the same as the pharmaceutical industry, showing neither the relative gains of the relatively large market nor the absolute gains; in the short-term dimension of the SARS outbreak range, during the period from April 18,2003 to May 16,2003, the four sub-sectors suffered a very limited decline, although they clearly outperformed the market.

1.3. Progress and diagnosis of the 2019-ncov epidemic

The 2019-nCoV, which caused the COVID-19, belongs to the same genus of coronaviruses as SARS, and the two viruses are similar not only in terms of their genotype and other biological characteristics, but also in terms of epidemiology and so on. However, as mentioned in part I, the 2019-nCoV is more infectious, but the severe case rate and mortality rate are not high at present. According to the Health Commission, the severe case rate of NCP is less than 20% , the mortality rate is about 2% , and the cure rate has already exceeded 10% , and the non-hubei area's critical illness rate and the mortality rate are lower, the cure rate is higher. As of February 20,2020, more than 40,000 patients had been diagnosed with the 2019-nCoV epidemic, five times as many as were finally diagnosed with the SARS epidemic, and 1,115 patients had died, slightly more than the SARS epidemic.

On the other hand, the inflection point of the 2019-nCoV epidemic may have emerged gradually. The number of newly confirmed and suspected cases of new coronary pneumonia has been decreasing continuously and the number of newly confirmed and suspected cases has started a downward spiral since 4 February 2020 and 5 February 2020 respectively; among them, the number of newly confirmed cases in non-hubei areas has declined for the eighth consecutive day. At present, the three-day extension of the Spring Festival holiday, the postponement of the resumption of work for 1-2 weeks in various regions and the "closure of cities, villages and roads" in some areas have indeed played an important role in curbing the development of the epidemic.

2. Impact of the 2019-ncov epidemic on the pharmaceutical industry

##2. Impact of the 2019-ncov epidemic on the pharmaceutical industry

2.1 changes in the pharmaceutical industry itself

The Chinese pharmaceutical industry itself has changed dramatically from 2003 to 2020, so the impact of an epidemic on the industry is bound up with the environment at different times.

During the SARS epidemic, China's pharmaceutical industry as a whole is still in the stage of wild growth, the industry is not large-scale, but the growth is higher, the overall domestic pharmaceutical environment is lack of medicine. In 2003, domestic expenditure on medicine and health was about 658.4 billion yuan, an increase of 14% year-on-year, of which the main business income of the pharmaceutical manufacturing industry was about 275 billion yuan, with a cumulative increase of 19% that year, the sub-industries with the largest contributions were 87.3 billion yuan for chemical agents, 76 billion yuan for chemical raw materials, 75.1 billion yuan for traditional Chinese medicines and 22.3 billion yuan for biological products.

New Crown Pneumonia, China's pharmaceutical industry has undergone earth-shaking changes, the size of the industry has become one of the world's leading. At the same time, although the overall growth rate of the industry has started to decline, the richness of the subsectors has greatly increased, and the industry nature of the pharmaceutical industry has gradually shifted from manufacturing to technology and consumption, although the overall problem remains large and weak. In 2018, China's medical and health expenditure was about 5,912.2 billion yuan, up 12 percent from the same period last year. It is estimated that the revenue of the pharmaceutical industry sector is about 2.5 trillion yuan, the largest subsectors are chemicals at $1.2 trillion, traditional Chinese medicines at $800 billion, medical devices at $550 billion and biological products at $200 billion.

The changes in the pharmaceutical sector in the a-share market are also consistent with the above description. From 2003 to 2020, the number of listed companies in the a-share pharmaceutical industry increased from 96 to 320, and the total market value of the industry increased from 260 billion to 4500 billion, the three subsectors that have contributed the most to the market capitalisation have shifted from traditional Chinese medicine, biologics and Apis to chemicals, medical devices and traditional Chinese medicines, while a number of previously non existent medical services, pharmaceutical businesses and others have sprung up.

Chart 12 top 5 a-share pharmaceutical companies by market capitalization, 2003

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chart 132020 A-SHARE pharmaceutical industry top 5 companies by market capitalisation

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Behind the changes in the volume and structure of the industry are more reserves and options for clinical diagnosis, treatment and medication, the weight of the medical system against the epidemic has increased rapidly since 2003, and more scientific and effective means of prevention and treatment have gradually gained popularity. For example, during the SARS epidemic in 2003, doctors were able to use only a limited number of diagnostic tests, and many people used products such as Radix Isatidis and white vinegar as prevention and even treatment. But during the NCOV in 2020, virus sequencing, image analysis and nucleic acid testing have been able to rapidly diagnose the disease. Although there is no specific drug for the new virus, over the years, the pharmaceutical industry has been able to rapidly offer a relatively rich selection of therapeutic products in the short term.

In addition to the great changes in the volume and structure of the industry, the operating logic of the industry has also undergone major changes.

In 2003, the basic medical needs in the country were far from being met, and only 100 million urban workers were covered by the health insurance fund, industrial firms that rely mainly on individuals for their payments and R & D capabilities lag behind or even have little innovation in R & D.

After the outbreak of SARS in 2003, the shortcomings of the inadequate construction of China's health care system began to be exposed after the reform and opening-up, and the government began to increase its investment. The new medical reform has become an issue of great concern to all sectors of society, the result is that after a long period of time, the government expenditure on health has increased rapidly, the coverage rate of residents' medical insurance has increased continuously, and the direction of medical reform has changed from "marketization" to "non-marketization" . Therefore, the medium-and long-term logic of the industry at that time was the expansion dividend at the payment end of the new health care reform, while the pharmaceutical industry, by virtue of the advantages of marketization and industrialization, welcomed the development opportunity which was superior to the medical service.

Chart 14 after SARS, the share of government spending on medicine and health began to increase

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chart 15 after SARS, coverage rates began to rise rapidly

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In 2020, China's pharmaceutical industry will still focus on meeting domestic demand, but the medical insurance fund has basically achieved full coverage of 1.4 billion people, and government health expenditure has become the main force of medical and health expenditure.

At the same time, medical insurance control fees, pay expansion dividends disappeared, the industry ushered in a structural adjustment: The value of medical services are gradually valued, the pharmaceutical industry as a whole is subject to price control growth continued to decline. In the medical service sector, the contradiction between the supply of and demand for medical resources, especially high-quality medical resources, is still very prominent. Social Medical Service, graded medical treatment and Internet medical treatment have become a new trend, innovation, curative effect and economy become new competitive elements, and transformation innovation and structural adjustment become the core logic at this time.

2.2 short-term impact of the outbreak on the pharmaceutical industry

In the short term, medical services unrelated to the pneumonia epidemic are being suppressed, as is the production and operation of the pharmaceutical industry. However, unlike other industries such as consumption, the Spring Festival period has been a slow season for medical service visits and the production and operation of pharmaceutical industry enterprises. Therefore, we believe that the negative impact of the epidemic is not large, but only a short-term impact, and because of the demand-driven nature of the service itself, most chronic disease visits may be delayed by only 1-2 months, and will not be suppressed.

For some industrial enterprises related to the epidemic, short-term demand has indeed increased significantly, but the impact on various sub-industries and enterprises still depends on the development progress of specific products, clinical effects and supply, at present mainly involves the medicine, the instrument diagnosis and the medical protection three big class products.

The first is pharmaceuticals.

There is no specific cure for the disease, but broad spectrum antiviral drugs, antibiotics, traditional Chinese medicines and biological products may be more commonly used in clinical settings, according to the COVID-19 and the disease itself, and therefore may benefit.

In the field of antiviral drugs, Ridgisivir, with its structural characteristics, in vitro studies and some clinical applications abroad, has become the most anticipated product in the medical community, and has now entered Phase III clinical trials through various fast-track channels, the clinical study is expected to be completed in late April. However, because of the urgency of the outbreak, it can not be ruled out that Radzivir can be rapidly applied through sympathetic treatment and other programmes on the basis of preliminary clinical results that confirm its safety and efficacy.

In addition to Ridgeville, other drugs on the market, including Lopinavir, Ritonavir, Interferon, Arbidol, and Favipiravir, have shown COVID-19 activity in vitro, therefore, although none of them has been studied clinically or has not been studied clinically, they are expected to be widely used in clinic.

Although guidelines have explicitly avoided the irrational use of antibiotics, many patients are middle-aged and elderly and prone to secondary bacterial infections, so an increase in the use of antibiotics during an outbreak is likely. However, because the outbreak is concentrated in Hubei Province and demand for many chronic diseases has been suppressed, leading to a decline in demand for antibiotics in other departments, the overall sales performance of antibiotics remains uncertain.

Because of the lack of specific drugs, the guidelines also recommend the treatment of traditional Chinese medicine and hormones: For patients with mild illness, the guidelines recommend such proprietary Chinese medicine and herbal pieces as Lianhua Qingwen, Huoxiang Zhengqi, Jinhua Qinggan, and for patients with moderate to severe illness, the guidelines refer to the use of methylprednisolone, Xuebijing injection, xiyanping injection as adjunctive therapy when necessary. For OTC proprietary Chinese Medicine (OTC PCM) , as it may have certain therapeutic effect on mild or severe cases and suspected cases, and is commonly found in pharmacies and other To c channels, we believe that in the short-term lack of specific drugs, "snap-up Shuanghuanglian" in the short-term may indeed exist, so some of the OTC short-term consumption may have more obvious growth.

Chart 16 outbreak-related drugs and corresponding companies

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Source: COVID-19

Vaccines are another focus of public concern. But the vaccine development cycle is long, based on recent developments, we believe that the new crown vaccine may eventually be developed after the market is not much, can only be used for storage. However, the outbreak is likely to increase public enthusiasm for second-class vaccines, such as influenza vaccines, in the medium and long term to increase the penetration rate of these products and accelerate industry growth.

Second is the field of instruments and diagnostics.

Detection and diagnosis is one of the busiest work links during the epidemic period, and the instruments with the fastest growth in demand during the epidemic period are mainly medical detection equipment and reagents, at present, the main diagnostic links are routine detection, imaging detection and nucleic acid detection.

Routine testing is the basic step of medical examination, which mainly involves the detection of white blood cell count, Myoglobin, etc. . The instruments used are blood cell analyzer, etc. . As the total number of routine tests is very high, considering the negative impact of the epidemic on other departments, it is estimated that this epidemic will not bring much flexibility.

Image detection is not only used in the preliminary diagnosis of suspected cases, but also in the diagnosis and management of patients with moderate or severe diseases. At present, about 15,000 DR units are sold annually in China. Due to the procurement and installation time and long service life of Dr and other large equipment, the epidemic may not generate much new procurement demand from hospitals in the short term, however, it is expected that this outbreak will further expose the problem of the backward capacity of county-level hospitals and further implement the policy of grading diagnosis and treatment, which will be conducive to the infiltration of medical equipment such as Dr into primary medical institutions in the medium and long term.

Chart 17 annual Dr Sales in China in recent years

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Source: China Industrial Information Network

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Nucleic acid detection is mainly used as a reference for the screening of suspected cases. At present, many domestic enterprises and institutions have developed and produced a new pneumonia nucleic acid test kits, basic to meet the needs of clinical testing. Because nucleic acid detection is mainly used for the screening of suspected cases of Reference, the unit price of the Kit itself is not high, its incremental elasticity is not expected.

In addition to detection and diagnosis, in clinical treatment, the demand for monitor, breathing machine, oxygen machine and other products will grow rapidly in the short term, and the purchase of these products by primary medical institutions is expected to contribute to a significant increase. Moreover, the appliance products with consumption attribute, such as breathing machine and oxygen making machine, are expected to further expand the out-of-hospital market by this outbreak.

And finally, medical protective products.

In this epidemic, the most prominent contradiction between supply and demand may be medical protective products such as face masks. According to the World Health Organization, China currently produces about 4.5 billion masks a year, half of the world's total, and exports the majority of them, but global demand has grown 100 times over the past year. Despite the extreme imbalance between supply and demand, due to capacity constraints and price control, the growth rate of medical protective products is limited, and the cost of labor and upstream raw materials rises during the Spring Festival, on the contrary, the profitability of the industry may decline.

However, in the medium and long term, although China has long been a major producer of medical dressings, the penetration rate of medical dressings such as medical protection is not high, and the current demand for medical dressings still mainly comes from developed countries such as Europe and the United States. China's medical dressing industry accounted for only 8 percent of the global market in 2016, according to BMI data, and the outbreak is expected to raise the awareness of medical institutions and the public on medical protection products.

2.3 medium-and long-term impact of the outbreak on the pharmaceutical industry

As noted earlier, the short-term impact of the SARS outbreak on the pharmaceutical industry was concentrated in one quarter and was primarily a disruption of supply and demand for industrial products and medical services. But in the long run, the SARS epidemic, as a catalyst, exposed many deficiencies in the public health field in China at that time, it also made the government and all sectors of society start to reflect on the loopholes in the public health system and the deficiencies in the construction of the medical security system since the reform and opening up, which gave birth to the new medical reform, the reform in the field of medical and health care is no longer just the supporting work of economic construction, but an important component of "scientific development" . Since 2003, the pharmaceutical industry has entered a golden growth period that is far higher than GDP growth, mainly because the government has increased the construction of the public health system and the health care system, the expansion of medical insurance and the increase of medical penetration rate make the industry step into a period of rapid development.

During the outbreak of Covid-19, China's health care system was also exposed to a number of shortcomings, such as limited medical resources and inadequate construction of primary care, the construction of the public health system needs to be strengthened, material reserves are insufficient and the level of new drug research and development is relatively backward. The corresponding reforms are also expected to speed up progress and bring about more new forms of business, have a profound impact on the long-term development of the industry.

The first is the contradiction between supply and demand of medical resources.

The main outbreak of the epidemic in Wuhan, where medical infrastructure is relatively developed and medical resources are relatively adequate, but after the outbreak of the epidemic, the shortage of medical resources is still very prominent. More than 20,000 health care workers already support Hubei and Wuhan, according to the National Health and Human Services Commission. The total number of registered health care workers in Hubei Province is about 300,000, while Wuhan is estimated to be less than 80,000, the supply of domestic medical resources is still insufficient. Moreover, the construction of primary health care in China is not perfect, the third-level hospitals have long become the norm, so in the outbreak of the conflict between supply and demand will be completely exposed.

At present, the solution to the shortage of medical resources is to increase the construction of primary medical facilities and promote the grading diagnosis and treatment. In general, the progress of grading diagnosis and treatment in the country is still slow, mainly because of the lack of infrastructure construction. However, this epidemic may be a catalyst to speed up the promotion of graded diagnosis and treatment. The recent meeting of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau also clearly pointed out that, "We should focus on overcoming the last bastion of the anti-poverty campaign and strengthen the improvement of rural human settlements and the construction of public health systems, taking epidemic prevention and control as the breakthrough point. ". And we believe that in the process of increasing the construction of primary medical facilities and promoting grading diagnosis and treatment, the biggest beneficiary may be the necessary medical device enterprises.

Internet medicine may accelerate the process from the bottom up in terms of marketization.

In this epidemic situation, the Internet medical service becomes the important channel which releases the medical establishment supply pressure. On the one hand, many hospitals around the world provide medical services through the Internet to solve the pressure of diagnosis and treatment of some common and chronic diseases; on the other hand, ali Health, chunyu doctor, tencent health, ping an Hao doctor, clove garden and other Internet medical platforms provide online consultation, epidemic prevention and epidemic tracking services to patients and the general public, relieves stress and cross-infection problems in physical health care settings.

In fact, the domestic Internet medical industry has been developing rapidly in recent years. In 2019 alone, the State Council, the National Health Commission, the State Medical Insurance Bureau and other departments issued a number of documents and measures to encourage the development of internet-based medical care. Rapid advances in technology have also enabled internet-based medical care to break through the limitations of traditional "consultation. " Complex diagnostic and therapeutic activities such as online consultations and even precision surgery are becoming a reality. We believe that the performance of Internet medicine in this epidemic is expected to support policy, consumer acceptance and other dimensions of the industry to bring revolutionary changes.

The second is the inadequacy of the public health system.

Although the financial expenditure on health and family planning is increasing year by year in China, the investment in public health is still insufficient. Over the past years, public spending on medicine and health care has been dominated by the expansion of health insurance coverage, while the public health system and even the hospital system have not been sufficiently developed. Therefore, after the outbreak of NCP, the direction of China's medical reform may focus on solving this problem, the investment of Public Health and medical institutions is expected to increase, and the procurement of new strategic reserve materials such as medical masks is also expected to increase.

For the medical institutions, the hospital infection control is an important part of the construction of public health system, hospital infection has been a difficult problem for medical institutions. No matter SARS epidemic situation, or the new pneumonia epidemic situation, hospital infection caused many medical staff infection or even death. After SARS epidemic, hospital infection began to get attention and control, but the intensity is still not enough. According to the 2017"Mrsa nosocomial infection strategy meeting" , the current incidence of nosocomial infection in China about 8% , each hospital infection in patients with an average of 14 days longer hospital stay, resulting in a direct national loss of more than 15 billion yuan per year. Therefore, we believe that this epidemic is expected to prompt medical institutions to step up their efforts in the prevention and control of nosocomial infections, and the procurement needs of disinfectants, protective clothing, medical masks, etc. May usher in a long-term inflection point, intelligent surgical robots and other high-end equipment may therefore be gradually attached importance to medical institutions and use.

For the general population, the outbreak will lead to a rapid improvement in the concept of public health prevention and medical science. During an outbreak, public demand for respirators, gloves, disinfectant and medical science knowledge surges and, more importantly, public awareness of prevention and attention to health may rapidly increase as a result, in the future such products and services are expected to maintain a high level of demand for the long term. We believe that the impact of the outbreak on household protection and device products, medical science and online consultation may be far-reaching.

Finally, the low level of research and development of new drugs.

Another glaring contradiction in the current outbreak is the mismatch between the public's demand for clinically effective drugs and vaccines and the ability and speed of companies to develop their products. On the one hand, because COVID-19 itself is a new virus, it is indeed difficult to quickly develop effective products, but on the other hand, this epidemic also reflects the backwardness of the domestic pharmaceutical industry, at present, several potential effective drugs are from foreign drug companies, the domestic R & D of New Drugs for the reserve is far from enough.

In recent years, the Food and Drug Administration and other government departments have been reforming the review and approval mechanism to speed up the release of innovative products. During the outbreak, a number of potentially effective drugs have also set records for clinical approval. We believe that policies will further encourage innovation and increase the enthusiasm of enterprises for research and development of new drugs that are urgently needed in society. In the industrial sector, the role of "innovation" will be further strengthened, and the main line of business will continue to be structural adjustment under the health insurance fee control.

3. Market Outlook

From January 20 to February 20, the pharmaceutical industry gained 2.47 percent, while the CSI 300 Index index fell 3.21 percent, with the pharmaceutical industry as a whole and subsectors outperforming the market. Combined with the previous judgment on the outbreak range, we think that the short-term volatility of the capital market is basically coming to an end.

Chart 21 since the beginning of the SHENWAN pharmaceutical industry outperformed the market by a wide margin

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Chart 22 years since the beginning of Shenwan Pharmaceutical sub-industry performance

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The industry is currently valued at about 40 times PE-TTM and trades at a premium of about 241 per cent to CSI 300 Index, both at levels not seen since 2019 and at medium highs since 2016.

In the short term, clinical development of OTC Chinese medicine, consumables for household and medical equipment and potential specific drugs related to the epidemic situation will accelerate; in addition, due to the new crown epidemic situation, in order to reduce the burden of small and medium-sized enterprises, the income of medical insurance will decrease in the short term. We can not rule out that the medical insurance should increase the control of expenses and pay more attention to the policy change of purchasing medicine and consumables in quantity.

In the long term, the medical industry may be affected by the epidemic to usher in new changes, the financial investment in the area of public health is likely to increase. We expect that the manufacturing industry will continue to focus on health insurance control fees, structural adjustment, and innovation-driven development, and that it will meet the industry's Long-term Development Direction of leading innovative drug companies and transform innovative traditional drug companies, products benefit from the rapid growth of medical device companies in the field of medical services, public health, graded diagnosis and treatment, as well as the construction of Internet medicine is expected to usher in a significant breakthrough, medical institutions and residents have increased awareness of protection, the Internet medical platform enterprises and medical protection products enterprises will be favored by the market.

Li Zhan is chief economist at Zhongshan Securities and Liu Yazhou is an assistant research fellow at Zhongshan Securities
